<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-086-205 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 124 205</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  August 5 1991 v2 n63 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Color laptop: RasterOps develops color display adapter for SonyNEWS RISC laptop workstation. (Sony NWU-LCB8 display adapter forNEWS 3250 computer) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   RasterOps Corp. (Product introduction)Sony Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    SNE.andO;Product:   Sony NEWS 3250 (Portable computer) (Product introduction)Sony NWU-LCB8 (Input-output device) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionLaptop computersI/O devices.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>RasterOps Corp. Tuesday announced an agreement with Sony Microsystems Co. toproduce the first high-resolution color display adapter for the Sony NEWS3250 RISC laptop workstation.andM;The product utilizes X-Windows to power large color displays in users'offices or projection systems used for presentations.andM;Under the agreement, the second between RasterOps and Sony in the last 60days, RasterOps will develop the Sony NWU-LCB8 laptop color display adapterto be sold and distributed by Sony Microsystems worldwide.andM;The Sony NWU-LCB8 plugs into the I/O slot in the laptop workstation systemand uses RasterOps' custom VLSI design to provide up to 256 colors.andP;  Theadapter supports VGA resolution of 640 x 480 pixels and SuperVGA/VideoMapresolution of 1024 x 768 pixels in 1, 2, 4 or 8-bit modes, and standardworkstation resolution of 1152 x 900 pixels in 1, 2 or 4-bit modes.andM;Under the control of X-Windows and a window manager such as MOTIF,applications may create images on the system's 1120 x 780 built-in monochromescreen and, in color, through a variety of VGA, SuperVGA and multi-frequencymonitors, as well as many standard overhead projection systems.andM;&quot;RasterOps' expanded relationship with Sony Microsystems is further evidenceof our commitment to provide sophisticated color capability forindustry-leading platforms,&quot; said Kieth Sorenson, RasterOps president andchief executive officer.andM;&quot;Workstation users have become very color-oriented, and we felt it wasimperative to provide this capability for our NEWS laptop workstation,&quot; saidDr. James Mannos, Sony Microsystems president.andP;  &quot;RasterOps' expertise indeveloping powerful, small form factor color controllers enabled us toquickly provide this color capability to our laptop customers.&quot;andM;RasterOps will begin delivering the NWU-LCB8 display adapter in September1991.andM;RasterOps Corp., headquartered in Santa Clara, designs, manufactures andmarkets photorealistic color-imaging products for the Apple Macintosh, IBMMicro Channel and Sun SPARCstation platforms.andP;  RasterOps products aredesigned primarily for the graphic arts, printing, publishing and relatedindustries.andO;</TEXT></DOC>